<font color=#00FFFF>@elder_man</font>

07:55.244 --> 07:56.244
(sighs)

07:59.154 --> 08:01.155
What the hell are you doing
in here?

08:01.190 --> 08:03.958
Kevin Slattery's been
waiting 20 minutes.

08:03.993 --> 08:05.827
- What?
- Kevin Slattery.

08:05.861 --> 08:07.295
Didn't Donna tell you?

08:07.329 --> 08:08.896
No, she, um--

08:08.931 --> 08:11.933
Harvey, what's going on?

08:11.967 --> 08:12.967
Nothing's going on.

08:12.968 --> 08:14.235
Why is Kevin Slattery here?

08:14.270 --> 08:15.670
He's looking for a new lawyer,

08:15.704 --> 08:16.971
and I'm looking for you
to close him.

08:17.006 --> 08:18.940
- Why me?
- Why not you?

08:18.974 --> 08:20.475
Because everybody
and their mother knows

08:20.509 --> 08:21.442
they're going bankrupt
in two weeks

08:21.477 --> 08:23.444
and I'm not a bankruptcy expert.

08:23.479 --> 08:24.646
Aren't you listening to me?

08:24.680 --> 08:26.914
He doesn't want to
declare bankruptcy.

08:26.949 --> 08:30.084
He wants you to
fight for him.

08:30.119 --> 08:32.520
Then he's come to me
on the right day.

08:32.554 --> 08:35.490
[dark music]

08:35.524 --> 08:37.825
♪ ♪

08:37.860 --> 08:40.128
Kevin, I hear you're looking
for a fight

08:40.162 --> 08:41.663
and I understand
we don't have much time.

08:41.697 --> 08:45.166
We don't, and I just wasted
half an hour waiting for you.

08:45.200 --> 08:47.735
So, before we get to anything,
you're gonna convince me

08:47.770 --> 08:49.737
why I should go with you
in the first place.

08:49.772 --> 08:51.306
Okay, we're done.

08:51.340 --> 08:52.807
Don't let the door hit you
on the way out.

08:52.841 --> 08:54.442
- What?
- You heard me.

08:54.476 --> 08:57.211
Only one of us is facing
bankruptcy and it isn't me.

08:57.246 --> 08:58.946
So instead of scolding me
for being late,

08:58.981 --> 09:00.141
you needed to be
convincing me

09:00.149 --> 09:01.683
why I should save
your dying company.

09:01.717 --> 09:03.551
So, nice to meet you.

09:06.255 --> 09:07.255
Loyalty.

09:11.860 --> 09:13.027
What did you just say?

09:13.062 --> 09:15.630
I have a game-changing contract
that's guaranteed

09:15.664 --> 09:20.001
to come my way in six weeks
if we can show solvency.

09:20.035 --> 09:21.135
Guaranteed by who?

09:21.170 --> 09:22.337
My college roommate.

09:22.371 --> 09:23.771
And you tell that
to your bankers,

09:23.806 --> 09:26.874
word gets out it's up for bid,
your competitors undercut you,

09:26.909 --> 09:28.949
and your roommate won't be able
to help you anymore.

09:28.977 --> 09:33.848
But if we make it six weeks,
we're back in business.

09:33.882 --> 09:35.149
And I guarantee
we'll never leave you.

09:35.184 --> 09:36.417
Here's the thing, Kevin.

09:36.452 --> 09:38.086
I don't give a shit about
a regional trucking company

09:38.120 --> 09:40.722
that's only going to increase
our billings 1%.

09:40.756 --> 09:42.390
I get you out of this,
your stock's gonna go

09:42.424 --> 09:43.858
through the roof.

09:43.892 --> 09:45.626
- You want a piece.
- I want 20%

09:45.661 --> 09:46.928
No way.

09:46.962 --> 09:49.030
You're the one coming to me.
Okay?

09:49.064 --> 09:52.700
80% of something is a whole lot
better than 100% of nothing.

09:52.735 --> 09:54.769
[stirring music]

09:54.803 --> 09:57.004
You gonna fight out there
like you just did in here?

09:57.039 --> 09:58.506
This is the preseason, Kevin.

09:58.540 --> 10:00.975
I haven't even broken a sweat.

10:01.009 --> 10:05.346
♪ ♪

10:05.381 --> 10:07.582
[sighs]

10:07.616 --> 10:08.850
Do you have a second?

10:08.884 --> 10:10.184
Yeah, sure.
What's going on?

10:10.219 --> 10:11.819
- Donna, are you shaking?
- I never should have

10:11.854 --> 10:13.688
- expected him to--
- What's going on?

10:13.722 --> 10:15.002
You know what?
Never mind. Sorry.

10:15.023 --> 10:16.958
Um...

10:16.992 --> 10:18.025
What did you want to
talk about?

10:18.060 --> 10:20.261
You never should've expected
who to what?

10:20.295 --> 10:22.063
What happened?

10:22.097 --> 10:24.098
I'm leaving Harvey.

10:24.133 --> 10:26.768
Oh, my God.

10:26.802 --> 10:28.202
Why?

10:28.237 --> 10:29.904
You remember when I told you
you could never go back,

10:29.938 --> 10:31.406
and then I said
I lied about that?

10:31.440 --> 10:34.308
Uh-huh.

10:34.343 --> 10:37.245
Turns out I was lying
when I said I lied.

10:37.279 --> 10:38.813
So you're just gonna leave?

10:38.847 --> 10:40.548
No, I'm going to
work for Louis.

10:40.582 --> 10:42.884
What? When?

10:42.918 --> 10:44.652
[laughs softly]

10:44.686 --> 10:47.555
Today.

10:47.589 --> 10:48.656
I'm sorry, Rachel.

10:48.690 --> 10:50.124
You didn't come in here
to talk about this.

10:50.159 --> 10:51.092
- What did you wanna talk--
- No.

10:51.126 --> 10:52.527
It's nothing.

10:52.561 --> 10:54.061
It can wait.

10:56.565 --> 10:58.666
- You got something for me?
- When don't I?

10:58.700 --> 11:00.968
I redid your shitty motion to
dismiss on Colter.

11:01.003 --> 11:02.236
My shitty motion?

11:02.271 --> 11:03.971
Yeah, your precedents
might as well have been

11:04.006 --> 11:05.440
Flintstone v. Rubble.

11:05.474 --> 11:07.909
Listen to me,<i> The Flintstones</i>
is an iconic classic

11:07.943 --> 11:09.243
that clearly
conveys the fact--

11:09.278 --> 11:10.445
- That you're old?
- Hey, you're the one

11:10.479 --> 11:11.579
who came up
with the reference.

11:11.613 --> 11:13.181
Which conveys the fact
that I'm smart.

11:13.215 --> 11:15.683
Wow, somebody took their
confidence booster shot

11:15.717 --> 11:16.884
- this morning.
- Actually, I took it

11:16.919 --> 11:17.885
last night.
And by took it,

11:17.920 --> 11:20.822
I mean I asked Rachel
to marry me.

11:20.856 --> 11:23.991
Oh shit, I wasn't supposed to
tell you that, but I just did.

11:24.026 --> 11:25.426
Then I won't say
congratulations yet.

11:25.461 --> 11:26.394
Oh, no, you can still say it.

11:26.428 --> 11:27.528
I can also say
I need a list

11:27.563 --> 11:29.330
of every one
of Slattery Corp's creditors,

11:29.364 --> 11:30.598
and I need it yesterday.

11:30.632 --> 11:32.433
Now, why would you say that
instead of congratulations?

11:32.468 --> 11:33.901
Because we have less
than two weeks

11:33.936 --> 11:35.136
to keep them out of bankruptcy

11:35.170 --> 11:37.090
and we can't do that
without knowing every person

11:37.105 --> 11:38.573
Kevin Slattery owes a nickel to.

11:38.607 --> 11:40.808
Harvey, that list is gonna be
over 50 names long.

11:40.843 --> 11:42.543
There's no way we can get to
all of them in two weeks.

11:42.578 --> 11:44.658
You know what? Instead of
telling me what we can't do

11:44.680 --> 11:47.281
and asking me for a copy
of <i> Brides</i> Magazine,

11:47.316 --> 11:49.317
why don't you just get the damn
list together?

11:49.351 --> 11:51.519
You told him we're engaged?

11:51.553 --> 11:53.387
I couldn't help myself.
But I wish I hadn't told him.

11:53.422 --> 11:54.422
Harvey, what's going on
with you?

11:54.456 --> 11:55.456
Nothing's going on.

11:55.457 --> 11:58.292
Congratulations.
There, I said it.

11:58.327 --> 11:59.427
Where the hell is my calendar?

11:59.461 --> 12:01.696
You know, I had it
right here yesterday.

12:01.730 --> 12:02.897
I don't know.
I'll go get Donna.

12:02.931 --> 12:05.099
No, don't get Donna.
I'll take care of it.

12:05.133 --> 12:06.067
What do you mean
don't get Donna?

12:06.101 --> 12:08.069
I said I'll take care of it.

12:14.443 --> 12:17.078
I've got it right here.

12:17.112 --> 12:19.413
Thanks, Rachel.

12:22.518 --> 12:23.451
[phone rings]

12:23.485 --> 12:26.387
[somber music]

12:26.421 --> 12:29.957
♪ ♪

12:29.992 --> 12:33.261
Harvey Specter's office.

12:33.295 --> 12:34.495
No, he's not available
right now.

12:34.530 --> 12:35.997
Can I take a message?

12:37.065 --> 12:39.000
Why didn't you tell him
about Donna?

12:39.034 --> 12:41.035
Because I knew Rachel knew,
and she'd tell him,

12:41.069 --> 12:43.237
and then I wouldn't have to
waste my time with it.

12:43.272 --> 12:47.108
Waste time or feel something?

12:47.142 --> 12:49.176
You think I wasn't feeling
something anyway?

12:49.211 --> 12:50.444
And what were you feeling?

12:50.479 --> 12:52.013
Right now,
I'm feeling this deposition

12:52.047 --> 12:54.115
- is never going to end.
- This isn't a deposition,

12:54.149 --> 12:55.716
and you're not getting out
of this that easily.

12:55.751 --> 12:57.418
You know what, I'm getting a
little tired of your attitude.

12:57.452 --> 12:58.686
And what attitude is that?

12:58.720 --> 13:00.388
The attitude where
I'm not gonna supply

13:00.422 --> 13:01.756
prescription narcotics
to someone

13:01.790 --> 13:03.157
who won't tell me
the truth?

13:03.191 --> 13:05.526
The attitude that says you know
me better than I know myself.

13:05.561 --> 13:07.562
I never said I know you better
than you know yourself.

13:07.596 --> 13:09.430
You said I'm keeping things
from you.

13:12.634 --> 13:14.502
And that's something you know
just as much as I do.

13:14.536 --> 13:15.836
Oh, bullshit.
I've been telling the truth

13:15.871 --> 13:18.339
this whole time and I haven't
left out a goddamn word.

13:18.373 --> 13:21.742
Okay, Harvey,
if that's how you wanna play it.

13:21.777 --> 13:24.078
I do know you
better than you know yourself.

13:24.112 --> 13:26.380
I had you pegged about
four seconds after you walked in

13:26.415 --> 13:28.449
my door, which is why I know
you weren't just

13:28.483 --> 13:31.852
washing your face
when Jessica walked in.

13:31.887 --> 13:34.855
You were washing your
face because you threw up.

13:34.890 --> 13:36.757
And you told yourself that you
were coming down with something

13:36.792 --> 13:37.992
or you had some bad clams.

13:38.026 --> 13:39.860
But I'll tell you
what really happened.

13:39.895 --> 13:42.964
You threw up because
you had a panic attack.

13:42.998 --> 13:44.165
And you're not coming to me

13:44.199 --> 13:46.500
because you're having trouble
sleeping.

13:46.535 --> 13:47.635
You're coming to me
because you're scared to death

13:47.669 --> 13:48.669
that it'll happen again.

13:48.670 --> 13:51.672
[dramatic music]

13:55.622 --> 13:57.872
Mike, can I talk to you
for a minute?

13:58.399 --> 13:59.866
What do you wanna talk about?

13:59.900 --> 14:01.201
Captain Dickhead back there?

14:01.235 --> 14:02.736
Look, I think maybe we should
cut him a little slack.

14:02.770 --> 14:04.337
No, I cut him some slack
when he barely acknowledged

14:04.372 --> 14:05.305
our engagement.

14:05.339 --> 14:06.373
Then I tried to get Donna
to help him

14:06.407 --> 14:07.641
and he bites my head off.

14:07.675 --> 14:10.143
What are you doing?

14:10.177 --> 14:11.778
Donna's leaving him.

14:11.812 --> 14:14.614
And she's going to
work for Louis.

14:14.649 --> 14:16.049
What the hell happened?
They've been through everything

14:16.083 --> 14:19.185
together.
What could possibly--

14:19.220 --> 14:20.687
Oh, my God,
they crossed the line.

14:20.721 --> 14:23.223
It's more complicated
than that.

14:23.257 --> 14:24.758
What does that mean?

14:24.792 --> 14:27.560
They crossed the line
years ago.

14:27.595 --> 14:28.728
You know what?
It doesn't matter.

14:28.763 --> 14:30.430
I don't need to no anymore.
Of course...

14:30.464 --> 14:32.532
we'll cut Harvey all the slack
in the world.

14:32.566 --> 14:33.967
Okay, I am going to stay late
and help him

14:34.001 --> 14:35.535
get everything in order.

14:35.569 --> 14:39.673
Hey, just keep in mind
that cutting him some slack

14:39.707 --> 14:40.974
is one thing.

14:41.008 --> 14:43.643
Doing Donna's job is another.

14:43.678 --> 14:45.145
It's just one day.

14:45.179 --> 14:47.313
It's not gonna last forever.

14:47.348 --> 14:50.283
[dark music]

14:50.317 --> 14:51.317
♪ ♪

14:55.623 --> 14:56.623
[clears throat]

14:57.925 --> 14:59.292
- How'd you find me here?
- Easy.

14:59.326 --> 15:00.560
I knew after this morning,
you'd come in here

15:00.594 --> 15:02.862
and your standard sandwich
of commiseration.

15:02.897 --> 15:04.064
I don't have a sandwich
of commiseration--

15:04.098 --> 15:07.000
Rueben on rye, with bacon
instead of Russian dressing.

15:07.034 --> 15:07.967
Well-done bacon.

15:08.002 --> 15:08.968
And if it's all the same
to you,

15:09.003 --> 15:10.370
I would prefer
to eat by myself.

15:10.404 --> 15:11.738
Fine.

15:11.772 --> 15:13.440
I just came in here
to give you this.

15:17.511 --> 15:18.511
You mean...

15:18.512 --> 15:20.146
Today is the day
I work for you.

15:20.181 --> 15:21.581
Oh, my God.

15:21.615 --> 15:23.817
I can't believe it.
This is really happening?

15:23.851 --> 15:24.951
What do we do first?

15:24.985 --> 15:26.186
I mean, I'm so goddamn
turned on right now.

15:26.220 --> 15:27.454
I don't know.
Maybe we could get a jump on

15:27.488 --> 15:29.422
some of the things that have
been piling up since Norma.

15:29.457 --> 15:31.458
Well, my Dictaphone's at full
capacity, it's about to burst.

15:31.492 --> 15:33.326
Well, I could help you
with that.

15:33.360 --> 15:35.061
- Would you?
- Of course.

15:35.096 --> 15:37.430
That's my job.

15:37.465 --> 15:38.798
Relieving the pressure
on your Dictaphone.

15:38.833 --> 15:41.134
Okay, you know what?
Maybe we're, um...

15:41.168 --> 15:42.102
moving too quickly.

15:42.136 --> 15:43.136
Okay.
Well, how about

15:43.170 --> 15:44.537
I just redo your calendar,

15:44.572 --> 15:46.773
and index every live case you
have, and then get to know

15:46.807 --> 15:50.143
every single inch
of your filing system.

15:50.177 --> 15:51.444
I don't think that's moving
less quickly.

15:51.479 --> 15:52.946
Culminating in that
inevitable moment

15:52.980 --> 15:54.080
when your phone finally rings

15:54.115 --> 15:56.716
and I say those
three magic words.

15:56.751 --> 15:57.817
Oh, good sweet Jesus.

15:57.852 --> 16:01.821
"Louis Litt's office."

16:01.856 --> 16:03.523
[hissing]

16:03.557 --> 16:05.125
God damn it, woman,
we're going back right now.

16:05.159 --> 16:06.526
Take care of the bill.
10% tip.

16:06.560 --> 16:10.163
Well-done bacon, my ass.

16:10.197 --> 16:12.632
He's totally not thinking
about sex right now.

16:12.666 --> 16:15.735
[lively music]

16:15.770 --> 16:17.470
Tell me you found
all 50 creditors.

16:17.505 --> 16:19.672
Not just all 50.
I found the one.

16:19.707 --> 16:21.141
How do you know
you found the right one?

16:21.175 --> 16:22.942
Because I know exactly
what you're gonna do.

16:22.977 --> 16:26.379
Then let me show you how
I'm gonna do it.

16:26.413 --> 16:27.413
[clears throat]

16:30.684 --> 16:32.385
[laughs softly]

16:32.419 --> 16:33.486
You're really gonna make them
do that?

16:33.521 --> 16:35.455
- Sure am.
- All of them?

16:35.489 --> 16:36.589
Doesn't work with some of them.

16:36.624 --> 16:37.724
North or South?

16:37.758 --> 16:40.293
Take your pick.

16:40.327 --> 16:41.995
Well, Harvey,
that's brilliant.

16:42.029 --> 16:44.764
There's only one problem.
It's illegal.

16:44.799 --> 16:46.833
Let 'em sue us.
It's civil, not criminal.

16:46.867 --> 16:49.969
Besides, we're bluffing anyway.

16:50.004 --> 16:52.405
What if I told you I have a way
to make it legal anyway?

16:52.439 --> 16:55.141
I'd say your idea
better work fast

16:55.176 --> 16:57.210
because we're going over there
in an hour.

16:57.244 --> 17:00.246
[lively music]

17:00.281 --> 17:01.848
(Harvey)
Vince Sanfillipo?

17:01.882 --> 17:03.850
[imitating Hannibal Lecter]
Yes.

17:03.884 --> 17:05.718
Is there a reason
you're not turning around?

17:05.752 --> 17:07.753
[imitating Hannibal Lector] I like to play
a little game with some of my visitors.

17:07.788 --> 17:09.923
For example,
you use Evian skin cream

17:09.957 --> 17:11.624
and sometimes you wear
L'Air Du Temps.

17:11.659 --> 17:13.726
- But not today.
- Of course I do.

17:13.761 --> 17:16.329
[as Clarice Starling] I'm just one generation
away from poor white trash.

17:16.363 --> 17:18.097
And I could only dream
of getting out.

17:18.132 --> 17:19.464
Getting anywhere.

17:19.500 --> 17:22.202
[imitating Hannibal Lector]
Getting all the way to the FBI.

17:22.236 --> 17:24.069
A census taker tried to
test me once.

17:24.104 --> 17:26.172
I ate his liver
with some fava beans

17:26.207 --> 17:27.773
and a nice Chianti.

17:27.808 --> 17:29.542
You see a lot, Doctor.
But are you strong enough

17:29.577 --> 17:31.878
- to point that high-powered--
- Quid pro quo, Clarice--

17:31.912 --> 17:32.912
All right.
That's enough.

17:32.947 --> 17:34.347
We didn't come here
for a quote-off.

17:34.381 --> 17:35.582
No, you didn't.

17:35.616 --> 17:37.584
You came here to get me
to give Kevin Slattery

17:37.618 --> 17:39.219
more time, and that's never
going to happen.

17:39.253 --> 17:41.788
Actually, we're here to get you
to buy up every piece of debt

17:41.822 --> 17:43.289
associated with Slattery Freight

17:43.324 --> 17:45.425
and then get you to give him
more time.

17:45.459 --> 17:46.626
And why would I do that?

17:46.660 --> 17:48.561
Why? Because you're the biggest
debtholder,

17:48.596 --> 17:50.230
and if any of the others
makes a claim,

17:50.264 --> 17:52.699
it'll trigger bankruptcy,
and you get 50 cents

17:52.733 --> 17:54.300
on the dollar five years
from tomorrow.

17:54.335 --> 17:55.702
You think I'm gonna
double down on a loser,

17:55.736 --> 17:57.303
because you can quote
<i>Silence of the Lambs?</i>

17:57.338 --> 18:00.740
No, you're gonna do it because
the day we file bankruptcy,

18:00.774 --> 18:02.976
every truck in that fleet's
going straight to Canada.

18:03.010 --> 18:05.645
And that 50 cents on the dollar
just hit 25.

18:05.679 --> 18:07.080
But that's illegal
and I will sue you

18:07.114 --> 18:08.681
and your client
into the ground.

18:08.716 --> 18:11.818
Well, it would be illegal if we
hadn't just a bought a defunct

18:11.852 --> 18:13.419
Canadian trucking company
for a dollar.

18:13.454 --> 18:14.487
Bullshit!

18:14.521 --> 18:16.022
Your covenants prohibits you
from doing that.

18:16.056 --> 18:18.791
Not if we do it before anyone
calls in our debt.

18:18.826 --> 18:21.995
Which we did.

18:22.029 --> 18:23.062
You're a son of a bitch.

18:23.097 --> 18:24.063
That's exactly what
I thought of myself

18:24.098 --> 18:25.298
when I came up with the idea.

18:25.332 --> 18:27.700
To be fair, I was the one
that came up with

18:27.735 --> 18:29.669
the defunct Canadian
trucking company thingy.

18:29.703 --> 18:30.770
- So...
- Oh, yeah, you're right.

18:30.804 --> 18:31.905
You're a son of a bitch, too.

18:31.939 --> 18:32.872
Oh, thanks, Harvey.
I appreciate that.

18:32.907 --> 18:34.974
Well, now that we agree
what we are,

18:35.009 --> 18:37.677
the question is, what are you
gonna do about it?

18:37.711 --> 18:40.613
[stirring music]

18:40.648 --> 18:42.248
♪ ♪

18:42.283 --> 18:43.683
What's so funny?

18:43.717 --> 18:45.718
I was just thinking
about that nutbag.

18:45.753 --> 18:47.220
Who starts a meeting off
like that?

18:47.254 --> 18:48.655
Yeah, you got to
give him credit, though.

18:48.689 --> 18:49.923
It was pretty fun.

18:49.957 --> 18:53.059
You think he's gonna do that bit
with the creditors?

18:53.093 --> 18:55.413
I don't care if he makes them
put the lotion in the basket,

18:55.429 --> 18:56.963
as long as he buys up
their debt.

18:56.997 --> 18:58.631
[as Buffalo Bill]
Or else it gets the hose again.

18:58.666 --> 19:02.902
(both) Wait, was she a great big
fat person?

19:02.937 --> 19:04.270
[laughs softly]

19:06.573 --> 19:07.907
Good job today, Mike.

19:07.942 --> 19:09.509
Thanks.

19:09.543 --> 19:11.077
Does this mean
I've earned the right

19:11.111 --> 19:13.980
for us to talk about
the Donna situation?

19:14.014 --> 19:15.415
There is no Donna situation.

19:15.449 --> 19:17.850
Harvey, come on, I know
you're not touchy-feely, but--

19:17.885 --> 19:19.218
Look, there's nothing
to talk about,

19:19.253 --> 19:21.621
because it isn't gonna last.

19:21.655 --> 19:24.624
[tense music]

19:24.658 --> 19:25.992
Okay.

19:29.031 --> 19:30.365
[door closes]

19:32.668 --> 19:34.403
- Hey.
- Hi.

19:34.437 --> 19:36.037
I got some Georgio's
reheating in the oven.

19:36.072 --> 19:38.407
Oh, you are my hero.

19:38.441 --> 19:40.041
Oh, I know.

19:40.076 --> 19:42.644
I mean, who says
that men can't cook?

19:42.678 --> 19:44.146
I think Georgio's does.

19:44.180 --> 19:47.649
- That's a fair point.
- Mm-hmm.

19:47.683 --> 19:49.851
So how was your test?

19:49.886 --> 19:52.788
Mmm...

19:52.822 --> 19:53.755
Whoa, it was that bad?

19:53.790 --> 19:54.990
You studied like crazy.

19:55.024 --> 19:57.893
No, it's not that
it was that bad.

19:57.927 --> 20:01.129
I just...

20:01.164 --> 20:02.431
I didn't take it.

20:02.465 --> 20:04.733
What do you mean
you didn't take it?

20:04.767 --> 20:06.935
I decided to stay late
and help Harvey.

20:06.969 --> 20:09.070
Help Harvey what?

20:09.105 --> 20:10.772
Never mind.
I know what.

20:10.807 --> 20:12.507
Something that would've been
done by Donna

20:12.542 --> 20:13.842
and should've been done by
his new secretary

20:13.876 --> 20:15.410
except he hasn't hired one yet.

20:15.445 --> 20:17.512
You're the one who said
we should cut him as much slack

20:17.547 --> 20:18.580
as he needs.

20:18.614 --> 20:20.348
I meant tolerating him
being a dick.

20:20.383 --> 20:22.083
Not you flunking out of school.

20:22.118 --> 20:24.352
The last time I asked Harvey
for time off,

20:24.387 --> 20:26.822
he told me
work is my law school,

20:26.856 --> 20:28.557
and he was right.

20:28.591 --> 20:33.762
I'm not gonna ask him for time
when he needs me the most.

20:33.796 --> 20:34.729
[laughs softly]

20:34.764 --> 20:36.298
What?

20:36.332 --> 20:37.332
- What?
- I was just thinking about

20:37.366 --> 20:39.334
when I asked you to marry me,

20:39.368 --> 20:41.036
I said how tenacious you are.

20:41.070 --> 20:42.704
Well, I know.

20:42.738 --> 20:44.105
It's like you should know what
you're getting yourself into.

20:44.140 --> 20:45.807
But you see what happens
when you don't wear that collar

20:45.842 --> 20:47.442
- on your finger?
- Stop it.

20:47.477 --> 20:49.911
[stirring music]

20:51.647 --> 20:54.449
I can't believe
you're really mine.

20:54.484 --> 20:57.452
Now, where would be
the perfect place to...

20:57.487 --> 20:58.687
Good morning, Louis.

20:58.721 --> 21:00.322
Holy shit. You just scared
the shit out of me.

21:00.356 --> 21:01.790
What are you doing here
so early?

21:01.824 --> 21:02.824
It's 8:15.

21:02.825 --> 21:05.060
Well, yeah, but we worked
late last night,

21:05.094 --> 21:06.461
and I told you to
take the morning.

21:06.496 --> 21:09.631
Louis, it's day two,
I'm not taking anything.

21:09.665 --> 21:11.800
Oh, shoot.

21:11.834 --> 21:13.935
I get it.

21:13.970 --> 21:15.070
You came in early
because you bought me

21:15.104 --> 21:16.605
an expensive gift
and you wanted to

21:16.639 --> 21:18.673
surprise me by putting it
on my desk.

21:18.708 --> 21:19.774
Something like that.

21:19.809 --> 21:22.544
Do you want me to go?
You can still surprise me.

21:22.578 --> 21:23.612
Never mind.

21:23.646 --> 21:26.281
Uh...
Being that you're here,

21:26.315 --> 21:28.316
I have a prospective client
coming in at 9:00.

21:28.351 --> 21:30.018
No, you don't.

21:30.052 --> 21:31.686
What do you mean?
The asshole canceled?

21:31.721 --> 21:33.955
No, the asshole intentionally
showed up an hour early

21:33.990 --> 21:35.724
and I sent him home,
telling him he was an hour late.

21:35.758 --> 21:37.526
What, are you crazy?

21:37.560 --> 21:38.960
That was Carl Fields, Donna.

21:38.995 --> 21:41.129
$12 million in billings
you let walk out the door.

21:41.163 --> 21:43.899
No, that's 12 million in
billings that's coming your way

21:43.933 --> 21:46.401
because now he knows you're not
someone to be trifled with.

21:46.435 --> 21:47.569
No, you can't know that.

21:47.603 --> 21:48.937
Really?
because I just got off the phone

21:48.971 --> 21:50.805
with his secretary, and they're
expecting you to come by

21:50.840 --> 21:54.042
with an engagement letter
in an hour.

21:54.076 --> 21:55.343
Holy shit!

21:55.378 --> 21:56.378
- Oh, shit.
- What?

21:56.379 --> 21:57.445
What's the problem?

21:57.480 --> 21:58.947
I'm still printing
to my old printer.

21:58.981 --> 22:00.148
What,
for the engagement letter?

22:00.182 --> 22:01.116
Donna, please,
you've done enough.

22:01.150 --> 22:02.817
Let me take care of it.

22:02.852 --> 22:05.453
[lively music]

22:05.488 --> 22:07.956
Like I wouldn't notice.

22:07.990 --> 22:10.258
♪ ♪

22:10.293 --> 22:11.793
There you go, little fella.

22:13.000 --> 22:19.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

22:23.773 --> 22:24.940
Hey.

22:24.974 --> 22:26.074
I was--
I was just...

22:26.108 --> 22:27.375
It's fine, Louis.
Whatever you were doing,

22:27.410 --> 22:28.450
- it's fine.
- Hey, Harvey,

22:28.477 --> 22:29.644
if there are
any hard feelings with Donna--

22:29.679 --> 22:31.046
No, Louis.
No hard feelings.

22:31.080 --> 22:32.280
Okay, but I just want to say,
if there was--

22:32.315 --> 22:34.983
I said there's
no hard feelings.

22:36.419 --> 22:38.253
As a matter of fact,

22:38.287 --> 22:41.489
why don't you tell Donna
I want her to have this?

22:53.369 --> 22:55.971
[dramatic rumbling]

22:58.608 --> 23:00.842
[poignant music]

23:00.876 --> 23:03.511
[in slow motion]
She's leaving you.

23:03.546 --> 23:06.448
[people laughing]

23:06.482 --> 23:14.322
♪ ♪

23:24.133 --> 23:25.700
You wanted to see me?

23:25.735 --> 23:27.135
That was an hour ago.

23:27.169 --> 23:28.169
Well, I just heard.

23:28.170 --> 23:29.204
And I just heard
the results

23:29.238 --> 23:31.206
of your little strong-arm tactic
with Mike.

23:31.240 --> 23:32.641
You mean you heard
that it worked.

23:32.675 --> 23:35.777
Oh, I know you got them
to do what you wanted.

23:35.811 --> 23:37.045
They bullied
all the other creditors,

23:37.079 --> 23:38.246
bought off all their debt,

23:38.280 --> 23:40.215
and they're going to back off
for eight weeks.

23:40.249 --> 23:41.383
Why do you seem pissed?

23:41.417 --> 23:43.485
Because you left a creditor
off the list.

23:43.519 --> 23:44.919
What?
How could that happen?

23:44.954 --> 23:47.155
I don't know how it happened,
but I know what it means.

23:47.189 --> 23:48.156
We're gonna get
held hostage.

23:48.190 --> 23:49.624
I'll take care of it.

23:49.659 --> 23:52.227
And if you can't take care of it
and Slattery goes bankrupt,

23:52.261 --> 23:54.021
you better figure out
a way to keep him here.

23:54.030 --> 23:55.330
What's that
supposed to mean?

23:55.364 --> 23:57.565
It means Jack Soloff's been
going around the firm

23:57.600 --> 23:59.601
saying you're never gonna
save that company

23:59.635 --> 24:01.703
and we don't have a plan
to retain their business

24:01.737 --> 24:02.871
when you don't.

24:02.905 --> 24:04.839
Since when do you care
about what Jack Soloff says?

24:04.874 --> 24:06.708
Since he's a senior partner
with ambition

24:06.742 --> 24:08.610
and you dropped the ball
twice in the two days.

24:08.644 --> 24:10.612
If you're so afraid of him,
why don't you just fire him?

24:10.646 --> 24:13.615
[laughs]
I'm not afraid of anybody,

24:13.649 --> 24:15.850
and I never said ambition
was a bad thing.

24:15.885 --> 24:17.218
- Jessica--
- Harvey,

24:17.253 --> 24:19.254
I don't know what's going on
between you and Donna,

24:19.288 --> 24:21.690
but I do know you chose
not to let me in on it,

24:21.724 --> 24:23.525
so I'm gonna let you in on this.

24:23.559 --> 24:25.226
If you can't figure out
how to get shit done

24:25.261 --> 24:27.562
without her, I will.

24:27.596 --> 24:30.832
[dramatic music]

24:30.866 --> 24:32.100
How'd it go
with Mr. Fields?

24:32.134 --> 24:34.169
Fine, but before you
dislocate your arm

24:34.203 --> 24:35.270
patting yourself
on the back,

24:35.304 --> 24:36.871
I need you to file those
before you leave today.

24:36.906 --> 24:38.039
All of them?

24:38.074 --> 24:40.308
Yes, all of them.
That's what "those" means.

24:40.342 --> 24:43.478
And then I want you to update
my Word Perfect by the morning.

24:43.512 --> 24:45.680
Louis, I have tickets
to the theater at 8:00.

24:45.715 --> 24:47.182
Second day and you're already
taking banking hours?

24:47.216 --> 24:49.451
Okay, I hardly think
8:00 constitutes--

24:49.485 --> 24:51.205
Norma worked till midnight
eight days a week

24:51.220 --> 24:52.220
and never bunted an eye.

24:52.221 --> 24:53.621
- Bunted?
- Yes, bunted.

24:53.656 --> 24:54.723
You have a problem
with my words now?

24:54.757 --> 24:56.057
Okay, Louis,
I don't know if you

24:56.092 --> 24:57.572
skipped your afternoon prunie
or what,

24:57.593 --> 24:59.060
but you're making me
feel uncomfortable.

24:59.095 --> 25:00.695
(Louis) Well, let's get
something straight.

25:00.730 --> 25:02.931
I'm not here to
make your life comfortable.

25:02.965 --> 25:05.100
You're here to do that for me.

25:05.134 --> 25:06.735
And the next time you print
something to the wrong copier,

25:06.769 --> 25:08.703
get it yourself.

25:08.738 --> 25:13.074
♪ ♪

25:13.109 --> 25:15.877
I gave you one job--
to find every single one

25:15.911 --> 25:17.812
of Slattery's creditors,
and you screwed it up.

25:17.847 --> 25:19.681
- What are you talking about?
- You left one off the list,

25:19.715 --> 25:22.417
and as soon as they realize that
we bought out everyone else,

25:22.451 --> 25:24.986
they'll know we have a deal
and they'll call in their debt

25:25.020 --> 25:26.354
and the whole thing
will blow up.

25:26.388 --> 25:27.956
Wait a second, they haven't
even called it in yet?

25:27.990 --> 25:29.157
No, they haven't
called it in yet,

25:29.191 --> 25:30.692
because they're gonna wait
till the last second

25:30.726 --> 25:32.006
so they can hold us
over a barrel

25:32.027 --> 25:33.528
because you didn't
do your job.

25:33.562 --> 25:35.730
and now I gotta find some
leverage on Katzen Financial.

25:35.765 --> 25:36.965
I didn't miss
Katzen Financial.

25:36.999 --> 25:38.266
Then why weren't they
on the list?

25:38.300 --> 25:42.103
I don't know, they were
on the list when I sent it--

25:42.138 --> 25:43.638
Goddamn Rachel.

25:43.672 --> 25:45.073
Harvey!

25:45.107 --> 25:46.641
Katzen was the last name
on that list

25:46.675 --> 25:48.443
and the only name on that page,
all right?

25:48.477 --> 25:50.044
The printer must have just
run out of paper.

25:50.079 --> 25:51.246
This isn't Rachel's fault.

25:51.280 --> 25:53.314
What am I supposed to tell
Kevin Slattery?

25:53.349 --> 25:54.716
"The reason you're losing
your company

25:54.750 --> 25:56.284
is because my associate
didn't load the printer"?

25:56.318 --> 25:57.786
I don't know, how about
you tell him the truth?

25:57.820 --> 25:59.187
That the reason he may
lose his company

25:59.221 --> 26:00.855
is because you didn't hire
a secretary.

26:00.890 --> 26:02.123
What the hell is that
supposed to mean?

26:02.158 --> 26:03.525
You know what it means.
Rachel has been killing herself

26:03.559 --> 26:05.326
to take care of you,
and we haven't said anything

26:05.361 --> 26:07.262
because we both agreed
to cut you some slack.

26:07.296 --> 26:08.530
- We?
- Yeah, we,

26:08.564 --> 26:09.798
but I'm not gonna let you
come down on her

26:09.832 --> 26:11.533
for screwing up something
that wasn't her job.

26:11.567 --> 26:13.201
Her job is to do
what I say,

26:13.235 --> 26:14.803
and you better wrap your head
around that.

26:14.837 --> 26:16.404
No, Harvey you better wrap
your head around the fact

26:16.438 --> 26:18.306
that Donna is gone and
she is not coming back.

26:18.340 --> 26:20.942
And I told you, it's not
gonna last with her and Louis.

26:20.976 --> 26:24.145
You keep saying that,
but all I see is Donna

26:24.180 --> 26:26.981
outside Louis's office
and no one outside yours.

26:27.016 --> 26:29.984
So you better swallow your pride
and ask her for help,

26:30.019 --> 26:32.854
or hire a new secretary,
but either way,

26:32.888 --> 26:35.690
you're done taking it out
on Rachel.

26:35.724 --> 26:38.726
[tense music]

26:43.525 --> 26:44.792
- [sighs]
- Hey, there, you got a minute?

26:44.826 --> 26:46.560
Barely.

26:46.595 --> 26:49.964
I need those two weeks
you offered me before.

26:49.998 --> 26:51.265
I'm afraid
it's too late for that.

26:51.300 --> 26:52.300
Donna, I'm drowning.

26:52.334 --> 26:53.701
This whole thing
with the Slattery deal is--

26:53.735 --> 26:55.736
I'm sorry about your deal,
Harvey, but you should have

26:55.771 --> 26:57.638
thought about that
before you turned me down.

26:57.673 --> 26:58.939
So you're punishing me?

26:58.974 --> 27:00.541
I'm not punishing you.

27:00.575 --> 27:02.343
But I have a mountain of work,
and even if I didn't,

27:02.377 --> 27:03.878
how do you think Louis
would feel if I suddenly

27:03.912 --> 27:05.072
started working for you
again?

27:05.080 --> 27:07.181
I don't give a shit
how Louis feels.

27:07.215 --> 27:08.883
Well, what about
how I feel?

27:08.917 --> 27:10.718
Which is that you're trying
to undermine my decision.

27:10.752 --> 27:13.354
How the hell am I trying
to undermine your decision?

27:13.388 --> 27:16.157
What do you call this?

27:16.191 --> 27:18.092
That--that was before--

27:18.126 --> 27:20.161
Before what?
Before you ran into Louis?

27:20.195 --> 27:22.029
Before you needed my help?
What?

27:22.064 --> 27:22.997
Donna--

27:23.031 --> 27:24.332
Do you know
where I found this?

27:24.366 --> 27:26.200
Louis put it right on top
of the list of secretaries

27:26.234 --> 27:29.403
that I have been keeping for you
because I still care about you,

27:29.438 --> 27:31.005
and you know what
they both did?

27:31.039 --> 27:32.840
They fed right into
his nightmare

27:32.874 --> 27:33.808
that I'm gonna
leave him,

27:33.842 --> 27:35.122
which is exactly
what you wanted.

27:35.143 --> 27:38.112
Do you know how hard it is
for me

27:38.146 --> 27:41.215
to swallow my pride
and come over here?

27:41.249 --> 27:43.417
Do you know how hard it is
for me to say no to you?

27:43.452 --> 27:44.752
(Harvey)
Then don't.

27:44.786 --> 27:46.854
I am asking you
for one little thing.

27:46.888 --> 27:48.622
No, Harvey, it's not
one little thing.

27:48.657 --> 27:51.092
Today it's the Slattery deal,
tomorrow's the Weiss merger,

27:51.126 --> 27:52.326
and then the day after that,

27:52.361 --> 27:53.527
it will be
a million other things

27:53.562 --> 27:56.797
until you think everything is
back to normal.

27:56.832 --> 27:58.966
(Donna) Well, it's not.
This is the new normal.

27:59.000 --> 28:02.670
This is my desk now, and I wish
I could help you, but I can't.

28:02.704 --> 28:04.472
Donna, please.

28:04.506 --> 28:06.173
I'm sorry, Harvey,
you're on your own.

28:06.208 --> 28:10.244
[heartbeat thumping]

28:10.278 --> 28:14.048
(Dr. Agard) And that's when it happened,
isn't it?

28:14.082 --> 28:16.550
You had another one.

28:16.585 --> 28:19.487
[heartbeat thumping]

28:19.521 --> 28:20.688
[sighs]

28:20.722 --> 28:21.922
I don't--I don't want
to talk about it.

28:21.957 --> 28:25.459
Step one to making them stop
is talking about it.

28:25.494 --> 28:26.694
[heartbeat thumping]

28:26.728 --> 28:31.098
I couldn't think,
I couldn't see, I c--

28:31.133 --> 28:32.533
I couldn't breath.

28:32.567 --> 28:33.701
(Dr. Agard)
And what did you do?

28:33.735 --> 28:35.035
(Harvey)
You know what I did.

28:35.070 --> 28:37.171
(Dr. Agard) No, I know.
I need you to say it.

28:37.205 --> 28:38.672
Why?

28:38.707 --> 28:41.742
'Cause the more you say it,
the less power it has over you.

28:41.777 --> 28:44.478
[heartbeat thumping]

28:44.513 --> 28:48.649
(Harvey) I made my way
into the bathroom,

28:48.683 --> 28:55.756
and my heart was p-pounding,
and my chest cracked open.

28:55.791 --> 28:58.659
[laughs]

28:58.693 --> 29:03.063
It was--it was like
I was under water.

29:03.098 --> 29:07.701
I looked at the stall,
and there was...two shoes there,

29:07.736 --> 29:10.337
a piece-of-shit brown shoe,
untied, two guys laugh--

29:10.372 --> 29:11.939
Yeah, and then?

29:11.973 --> 29:13.107
[heartbeat accelerating]

29:13.141 --> 29:15.276
(Harvey) [sighs]
I ran to the stall, I threw up,

29:15.310 --> 29:17.378
and I just waited
until it was over.

29:17.412 --> 29:20.247
[toilet flushing]

29:20.282 --> 29:22.383
(Dr. Agard) And that's the night
you came to see me.

29:22.417 --> 29:24.151
Yeah.

29:24.186 --> 29:26.720
And you made up a story
about having trouble sleeping

29:26.755 --> 29:30.191
to get antianxiety medication,

29:30.225 --> 29:32.827
and you've been taking
a pill a day since.

29:32.861 --> 29:33.861
Yes.

29:33.862 --> 29:34.862
[heartbeat pounding]

29:40.101 --> 29:42.069
Busy.

29:45.507 --> 29:48.442
Louis...

29:48.477 --> 29:49.477
I'm not leaving you.

29:49.511 --> 29:51.245
It says,
"Replacements for Louis"

29:51.279 --> 29:54.648
Right here on top,
"replacements for Louis."

29:54.683 --> 29:57.885
That's because that's the list
I made after Norma died.

29:57.919 --> 29:59.386
Then why do you still
have it?

29:59.421 --> 30:01.489
Because I was saving it
for Harvey.

30:01.523 --> 30:02.690
This is for Harvey?

30:02.724 --> 30:05.793
Yes, Louis, because I work
for you now,

30:05.827 --> 30:07.928
and I'd like to tell you
to stop questioning

30:07.963 --> 30:09.296
whether I'm gonna
change my mind,

30:09.331 --> 30:11.011
but we both know
that's never gonna happen,

30:11.032 --> 30:15.135
so instead, I'll say...

30:15.170 --> 30:16.871
you need to talk to me about it
when it does.

30:16.905 --> 30:18.839
But I did talk to you,
Donna.

30:18.874 --> 30:21.075
First, I loaded you up
with work, then I yelled at you,

30:21.109 --> 30:22.910
and then I put the can-opener
on top of that list.

30:22.944 --> 30:24.311
I mean, I can't be
more direct than that.

30:24.346 --> 30:27.147
Yes, you can, Louis.

30:27.182 --> 30:29.783
Because I don't want that kind
of relationship anymore.

30:29.818 --> 30:31.886
What's it for?

30:31.920 --> 30:32.920
What's what for?

30:32.954 --> 30:36.991
(Louis)
The can opener.

30:37.025 --> 30:38.459
It's just a can opener,
Louis.

30:38.493 --> 30:40.427
No, it's not.

30:40.462 --> 30:43.264
Harvey was sending me a message
when he gave it to me.

30:43.298 --> 30:45.266
That message wasn't meant
for you.

30:45.300 --> 30:46.500
It was meant for me.

30:46.535 --> 30:47.868
Donna, you want me
to talk to you,

30:47.903 --> 30:52.573
but now you're not
talking to me.

30:52.607 --> 30:54.909
It was a ritual
that Harvey and I would do

30:54.943 --> 30:56.310
before we went to trial.

30:56.344 --> 30:58.579
So the message was,

30:58.613 --> 31:03.250
Donna, you'll never have
something like that with me.

31:03.285 --> 31:04.365
No, Louis,
that's not what--

31:04.386 --> 31:08.322
We should have a ritual.

31:08.356 --> 31:12.326
Let's worry about that
after we win our first big case.

31:12.360 --> 31:15.329
[gentle music]

31:15.363 --> 31:17.031
♪ ♪

31:27.048 --> 31:29.083
I was just about to offer you
one of those.

31:29.117 --> 31:30.718
Jessica, if you're here
to yell at me again--

31:30.752 --> 31:32.353
I'm not here
to yell at you.

31:32.387 --> 31:34.121
I'm here to
apologize to you.

31:34.155 --> 31:37.525
Then you can have a drink.

31:37.559 --> 31:40.961
The truth is,
there's a time for yelling

31:40.996 --> 31:43.864
and there is a time
for understanding,

31:43.899 --> 31:46.100
and a good partner
knows the difference.

31:46.134 --> 31:47.935
You mean
a good managing partner.

31:47.969 --> 31:51.472
No, I mean
a good partner.

31:51.506 --> 31:54.475
The night you found out
Donna was in trouble,

31:54.509 --> 31:57.845
the first thing you did
was take the time...

31:57.879 --> 32:01.615
to have a drink with me
about Jeff.

32:01.650 --> 32:03.617
So the least I could do
is take the time

32:03.652 --> 32:05.452
and understand
your situation.

32:05.487 --> 32:07.521
You mean, the fact
that I don't have a secretary.

32:07.556 --> 32:09.516
I mean that after 12 years,
the woman you wouldn't

32:09.524 --> 32:12.860
come work here without
is now working for someone else.

32:12.894 --> 32:14.995
And you want to know why.

32:15.030 --> 32:16.697
I don't need to know why.

32:16.731 --> 32:20.401
I need to know if you want me
to undo it.

32:20.435 --> 32:22.970
What?

32:23.004 --> 32:25.205
I know you and Donna
aren't me and Jeff,

32:25.240 --> 32:28.976
but you are as close
as two people can be

32:29.010 --> 32:30.544
without being that.

32:30.579 --> 32:32.580
Shit, Harvey,
Scottie leaving

32:32.614 --> 32:34.281
didn't throw you off your game
this much.

32:34.316 --> 32:38.085
I appreciate the offer.

32:38.119 --> 32:42.690
But as long as Donna wants
to work for Louis,

32:42.724 --> 32:44.892
I am not gonna force her
to work for me.

32:44.926 --> 32:47.528
Okay.

32:47.562 --> 32:50.464
[somber music]

32:50.498 --> 32:54.835
♪ ♪

32:54.869 --> 32:57.371
Harvey,
have you thought about

32:57.405 --> 33:00.741
what's going to happen
if she doesn't come back?

33:00.775 --> 33:03.043
She will.

33:03.078 --> 33:09.650
♪ ♪

33:09.684 --> 33:11.719
(Dr. Agard)
Wow.

33:11.753 --> 33:13.520
Wow what?

33:13.555 --> 33:15.389
This Jessica sounds like
a hell of a woman.

33:15.423 --> 33:16.857
What does that have to do
with anything?

33:16.891 --> 33:18.225
No, it doesn't.
I-I was just--

33:18.259 --> 33:19.860
Look, I don't care
what you were doing.

33:19.894 --> 33:22.930
We've been here
long enough.

33:22.964 --> 33:25.766
Hmm, we have.

33:25.800 --> 33:27.601
But I'm not gonna give you
another prescription.

33:27.636 --> 33:28.836
You said if I opened up--

33:28.870 --> 33:31.005
I said if you didn't,
I wouldn't.

33:31.039 --> 33:32.673
I didn't say if you did,
I would.

33:32.707 --> 33:33.641
They're not
the same thing.

33:33.675 --> 33:34.908
Goddamn it.

33:34.943 --> 33:38.312
Hold on, you didn't
let me finish.

33:38.346 --> 33:42.116
I'm not gonna write you
another prescription.

33:42.150 --> 33:46.654
I'm gonna give you these.

33:46.688 --> 33:48.689
That's enough
for another week.

33:53.995 --> 33:55.262
You want me to come
in here again.

33:55.296 --> 33:57.164
Mm, I sure do.

33:57.198 --> 34:00.300
Or you can roll the dice
and spread them out,

34:00.335 --> 34:02.936
but you're not getting anymore
without seeing me again.

34:05.106 --> 34:08.074
[moody pop music]

34:08.109 --> 34:09.143
♪ ♪

34:09.177 --> 34:12.012
One more thing.

34:12.047 --> 34:13.681
These episodes are gonna
keep happening

34:13.715 --> 34:17.184
until you accept the fact
that Donna may never come back.

34:17.217 --> 34:25.225
♪ ♪

34:45.447 --> 34:47.313
Where the hell have you been
all morning?

34:47.348 --> 34:48.449
What are you, my mother?

34:48.483 --> 34:50.117
I was at a meeting.
Why?

34:50.150 --> 34:51.318
Remember when you said
Katzen was gonna

34:51.351 --> 34:53.420
wait till the last second
to hold us over a barrel?

34:53.455 --> 34:55.556
Well, they didn't.
They sold all of their debt

34:55.590 --> 34:58.292
to Kevin Slattery's
biggest competitor.

34:58.326 --> 35:00.661
They're gonna want to put us
in the ground for good.

35:00.695 --> 35:02.129
Well, then it's a good thing
I figured out a way

35:02.163 --> 35:04.998
to convince 'em not to.

35:05.033 --> 35:06.600
What the hell are we still
doing here?

35:06.634 --> 35:07.701
You tell me.

35:07.736 --> 35:15.743
♪ ♪

35:18.980 --> 35:20.814
What the hell happened?

35:20.849 --> 35:22.883
Atlantic Freight
is my chief rival.

35:22.917 --> 35:23.951
If they call in the debt,

35:23.985 --> 35:25.686
they'll force me
into bankruptcy.

35:25.720 --> 35:27.121
If they call in
the debt.

35:27.155 --> 35:28.489
What is he talking about?

35:28.523 --> 35:29.823
He's talking about the fact
that we just came from

35:29.858 --> 35:31.358
a meeting with them,
and you're right.

35:31.392 --> 35:33.026
They'd love nothing more
than to put you down

35:33.061 --> 35:33.994
once and for all.

35:34.028 --> 35:35.028
Goddamn it.

35:35.063 --> 35:36.530
But lucky for you,
we told them

35:36.564 --> 35:38.265
that if they force you
into bankruptcy,

35:38.299 --> 35:40.400
that doesn't necessarily
kill your company,

35:40.435 --> 35:42.069
but buying
your name does.

35:42.103 --> 35:45.272
So they own me?
That's your brilliant solution?

35:45.306 --> 35:47.274
No, they own
the Slattery trademark,

35:47.308 --> 35:49.243
which they think
effectively puts you under,

35:49.277 --> 35:50.611
but they don't know
what we know.

35:50.645 --> 35:51.578
And what is that?

35:51.613 --> 35:52.946
That you have
another contract

35:52.981 --> 35:55.082
that doesn't care
about the name of your company.

35:55.116 --> 35:56.750
They only care
about the name of the owner.

35:56.785 --> 35:59.753
How the hell did Katzen
even know to sell their debt?

35:59.788 --> 36:01.655
Because I made a mistake.

36:01.689 --> 36:03.290
You sure as hell did!

36:03.324 --> 36:05.592
After asking for 20%
of my company

36:05.627 --> 36:07.661
and bragging that
you could save it.

36:07.695 --> 36:10.164
Well, it turns out it, you're
just an arrogant mouthpiece

36:10.198 --> 36:12.699
that thinks he can
save anything.

36:12.734 --> 36:13.767
But you can't.

36:13.802 --> 36:17.905
Kevin, nobody hates change
more than I do,

36:17.939 --> 36:20.307
but it's coming
whether we like it or not.

36:20.341 --> 36:23.210
And if I could save
both your company and your name,

36:23.244 --> 36:27.281
I would,
but you're right, I can't.

36:27.315 --> 36:30.384
So take the deal, wake up
tomorrow, and go to work.

36:30.418 --> 36:33.353
[stirring music]

36:33.388 --> 36:39.259
♪ ♪

36:43.965 --> 36:45.799
Hey, Harvey?

36:45.834 --> 36:48.569
Yeah.

36:48.603 --> 36:51.171
I just want to say
thanks...

36:51.206 --> 36:53.674
for not throwing us
under the bus back there.

36:53.708 --> 36:54.975
What do you mean?

36:55.009 --> 36:58.345
Well, I mean, you could have
told Slattery the truth.

36:58.379 --> 37:01.081
That mistake was
mine and Rachel's.

37:01.115 --> 37:03.116
No it wasn't.

37:03.151 --> 37:05.786
You were right,
that mistake was mine.

37:05.820 --> 37:08.789
[poignant music]

37:08.823 --> 37:13.961
♪ ♪

37:13.995 --> 37:15.435
Hey. What are you
doing here so late?

37:15.463 --> 37:17.197
You didn't hear?

37:17.232 --> 37:18.765
We closed
the Davis brothers.

37:18.800 --> 37:20.334
- That's huge.
- It is.

37:20.368 --> 37:23.070
So I thought maybe
this was the perfect time

37:23.104 --> 37:24.471
to start our ritual.

37:24.505 --> 37:28.809
Oh, Donna, listen,
I've been thinking.

37:28.843 --> 37:29.910
I don't think we don't need
to have a ritual.

37:29.944 --> 37:32.913
Come on.
It's our first big win.

37:38.953 --> 37:40.988
That's the same exact cake
I got Mike.

37:41.022 --> 37:41.955
I know.

37:41.990 --> 37:44.091
How did you know?

37:44.125 --> 37:45.659
I'm Donna.

37:45.693 --> 37:47.427
[laughs softly]

37:47.462 --> 37:49.730
You sure are.

37:49.764 --> 37:51.265
What flavor is it?

37:51.299 --> 37:53.433
Well, I called Esther,
and she said

37:53.468 --> 37:55.002
German Chocolate was
your favorite.

37:55.036 --> 37:56.036
I hate German Chocolate.

37:56.037 --> 37:57.671
Which is why I got you
Mocha Fudge.

37:57.705 --> 37:59.873
It's perfect.

37:59.908 --> 38:01.875
[sniffs]

38:04.746 --> 38:06.813
What can I do for you,
Harvey?

38:06.848 --> 38:09.983
I just wanted to see
if you still had that list.

38:10.018 --> 38:11.485
Of course I do.

38:22.964 --> 38:25.465
[heartbeat thumping]

38:25.500 --> 38:26.934
[door opens]

38:26.968 --> 38:29.937
[heartbeat thumping]

38:55.296 --> 38:58.265
[rousing pop music]

38:58.299 --> 39:06.306
♪ ♪

39:22.924 --> 39:28.595
♪ ♪

39:33.134 --> 39:34.468
What's this?

39:34.502 --> 39:37.337
Your engagement present.

39:37.372 --> 39:38.739
Come on, Rachel,
how long did you think

39:38.773 --> 39:40.007
you could keep
that glow a secret?

39:40.041 --> 39:41.108
I'm glowing?

39:41.142 --> 39:43.176
Like Times Square
on New Year's Eve.

39:43.211 --> 39:44.478
To me.

39:44.512 --> 39:45.812
The rest of the world
can't even see you

39:45.847 --> 39:48.215
under that pile of work
you took on to help Harvey.

39:48.249 --> 39:49.850
You knew about that too?

39:49.884 --> 39:50.984
Of course I did,

39:51.019 --> 39:53.887
which is why
you're getting this.

39:55.223 --> 39:56.223
Donna,
you didn't have to--

39:56.257 --> 39:58.392
I didn't,
but Harvey did.

39:58.426 --> 40:00.193
And he won't think
to get you two a gift,

40:00.228 --> 40:01.328
'cause I was always
the one

40:01.362 --> 40:03.263
who took care of things
like that, so...

40:03.297 --> 40:05.432
I don't know what to say.

40:05.466 --> 40:06.466
Say thank you.

40:06.467 --> 40:07.934
Thank you.

40:07.969 --> 40:10.170
And promise me,

40:10.204 --> 40:14.107
no matter what is going on
in my life,

40:14.142 --> 40:19.179
you won't feel bad about telling
me all the good things in yours.

40:19.213 --> 40:20.981
I promise.

40:21.015 --> 40:23.984
[stirring music]

40:24.018 --> 40:28.387
♪ ♪

40:32.526 --> 40:33.558
What is this?

40:33.592 --> 40:35.227
(Harvey)
A copy of <i>Brides</i> Magazine.

40:35.261 --> 40:36.694
Why is it on my desk?

40:36.729 --> 40:38.196
How else are you gonna
pick your colors?

40:38.231 --> 40:40.632
Colors?
What are colors?

40:40.666 --> 40:41.866
How do <i>you</i> know
what they are?

40:41.901 --> 40:43.268
Because I'm a grown man.

40:43.302 --> 40:44.903
Really? 'Cause you sound
more like a grown woman.

40:44.937 --> 40:46.104
That's very hurtful.

40:46.139 --> 40:49.141
I looked everywhere
for that issue.

40:50.308 --> 40:51.975
Thanks, Harvey.

40:52.010 --> 40:53.177
Thank me on the way.

40:53.211 --> 40:54.578
Where are we going?

40:54.612 --> 40:57.415
To do what we should have done
the day you got engaged.

40:57.449 --> 40:58.516
Nets game.

40:58.550 --> 41:00.217
Are you kidding?

41:00.252 --> 41:01.919
Front row.

41:01.953 --> 41:04.788
Holy shit.
Is Jay-Z gonna be there?

41:04.822 --> 41:05.956
Yeah, right next to me.

41:05.990 --> 41:07.890
Next to you?
Wait, this my gift, hey.

41:07.925 --> 41:09.926
I don't care whose gift it is.
I'm not doing that to Jay-Z.

41:09.960 --> 41:11.661
Oh, you know what,
I'll just sit next to Beyoncé.

41:11.695 --> 41:12.862
We'll call it a draw.

41:12.896 --> 41:15.131
You know what, never mind.
I'm taking Rachel.

41:15.166 --> 41:16.799
Yeah, well, why don't you just
give it to both of us?

41:16.833 --> 41:20.070
Oh, wait, then who would
stay here and do all your work?

41:20.104 --> 41:21.971
Shit.
Was that too soon?

41:22.005 --> 41:24.206
Oh, I'm so sorry, bud.
Let's go!

41:24.240 --> 41:25.240
[rousing pop music]

